The paper focuses on solving Ordinary Differential Equations (ODEs) in the domain of neuroscience using reduced-precision fixed-point arithmetic types. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the potential improvements in energy efficiency and memory footprint and bandwidth, which are relevant to the Modeling and Simulation (cs.MS) and Architecture (cs.AR) sub-categories. The paper also investigates the accuracy of fixed-point arithmetic types, which is relevant to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions that the results will have implications for the solution of ODEs in other subject areas, which suggests that the Scientific Computing (cs.SC) sub-category is also relevant.
